<HEADLINE>
<P>
NORTHWEST'S BATTLE OVER TREES AND JOBS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
For years I have been reading how our environmentalists have been prodding 
Brazil and other Third World countries to save the rain forests because of the 
damaging effect this destruction would have on global climate, to say nothing 
of air for breathing. 
</P>
<P>
Yet we have a constant battle to preserve our national parks, as well as our 
coastlines (regarding oil) from exploitation. 
</P>
<P>
Isn't our country strong enough to afford these "luxuries?" What are we going 
to leave for our descendants? Bare bones and ravaged earth? 
</P>
<P>
And if we are ever in such desperate straits that we're forced to use them, 
they will still be there. If we use them up now, what then? 
</P>
<P>
If lumber companies want trees, why do they not plant them? If they had done 
this in the past, there would have been plenty available. And it is not too 
late to start now. (Apologies to any company which has been doing this.) 
</P>
<P>
SAM BARON 
</P>
<P>
Inglewood 
</P>
</TEXT>
