<HEADLINE>
<P>
DR. NEIL SOLOMON: SEX AND AGING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. NEIL SOLOMON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: I am a newly single woman who is getting very close to her 60th 
birthday. At a recent party that I attended, I was handed a line that I had not 
heard since I was in college many years ago. 
</P>
<P>
During a conversation with one of the men there, he remarked that having sexual 
relations is good for a woman's health. When I told him that he reminded me of 
a teen-ager I once knew, he insisted he was serious. Is there anything to this? 
</P>
<P>
A: Having sexual relations can help a woman maintain her genital health. It has 
been reported that among women 60 to 70 years of age, those who engage in 
sexual relations experience less vaginal atrophy and have better lubrication. 
It should be apparent, however, that engaging in indiscriminate sexual 
relationships is not a prescription for good health, genital or otherwise, for 
either men or women. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
