</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Colombia has more than doubled the reward for information leading to the arrest 
of drug lord Pablo Escobar to almost $1 million, according to a new army 
pamphlet. 
</P>
<P>
Soldiers handed out the pamphlets in Colombia's cocaine center of Medellin 
during the weekend, offering $960,000 for information on Escobar, residents 
said. The new amount is more than twice the $385,000 reward previously offered 
for Escobar, the boss of the Medellin cocaine cartel. The authorities regard 
him as public enemy No. 1, responsible for ordering scores of bombings and the 
assassinations of dozens of people. 
